Santana&#039;s 1970 follow-up to their Woodstock-propelled smash &#039;69 debut 
found leader Carlos Santana further expanding his San Francisco group&#039;s 
already broad musical boundaries. To wit: two hit singles that emanated from 
opposite ends of the spectrum--"Black Magic Woman," originally written and 
recorded by English blues-rock guitarist Peter Green and Fleetwood Mac, and 
New York Latin percussionist/dance music king Tito Puente&#039;s infectious "Oye 
Como Va." Tying blues, rock, and salsa together in one pancultural package, 
Abraxas also featured such standout tracks as "Gypsy Queen" and "Singing 
Winds, Crying Beasts." The latter underscored the growing Eastern 
sensibilities of guitarist Santana. --Billy Altman
